## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical application of 3-valued logic in policy-like constraints with a concrete propagation strategy.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene 3-valued logic with On= T, Off= F, Unknown= U
- Implication semantics and unknown propagation
- Forward/backtracking CSP approach to avoid F states

## Code Example
```javascript
function kleeneVal(a,b){ // a,b in {T,F,U}
  if(a==="F") return "T";
  if(a==="T" && b==="F") return "F";
  if(a==="T" && b==="T") return "T";
  return "U";
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you scale to n services with a mix of constraints?
- What if cycles exist or new constraints are added dynamically?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests extending Boolean logic to 3-valued systems with biconditionals in realistic feature-flag scenarios, plus constraint propagation and backtracking techniques.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene 3-valued logic for →, ∧, ∨ operations
- Biconditional as (A→B) ∧ (B→A)
- Constraint propagation with Unknown handling and backtracking
- Feature-flag rollout scenarios with partial information

## Code Example
```javascript
// Kleene values: F < U < T
const rank = {F:0, U:1, T:2};
function not(v){ return v==='T'?'F': v==='F'?'T':'U'; }
function implies(a,b){ const na = not(a); return [na, b].reduce((x,y)=>rank[x]>=rank[y]?x:y); }
function and(a,b){ return [a, b].reduce((x,y)=>rank[x]<=rank[y]?x:y); }
function or(a,b){ return [a, b].reduce((x,y)=>rank[x]>=rank[y]?x:y); }
```

## Approach
The propagation algorithm iteratively applies constraints, treating U as flexible until forced to T or F. When conflicts arise, it backtracks systematically through the remaining U values.

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design a small CSP with Kleene semantics, reason about propagation, and craft a concrete counterfactual assignment with U, plus depth-limited reasoning.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene three-valued logic: T>U>F; ¬ maps T↔F, U↔U.
- Implication as ¬X ∨ Y; F only when antecedent is T and consequent F.
- Depth-limited backtracking with constraint propagation to avoid exploring futile branches.

## Code Example
```javascript
function kleeneNot(v){ return v==='T'?'F':v==='F'?'T':'U';}
function kleeneOr(a,b){ return a==='T'||b==='T'?'T': a==='U'||b==='U'?'U':'F';}
function kleeneImp(a,b){ // a -> b
  if(a==='T' && b==='F') return 'F';
  if(a==='T' && b==='U') return 'U';
  if(a==='F') return 'T';
  if(a==='U' && b==='F') return 'U';
  return (b==='T') ? 'T' : 'U';
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would adding a 6th variable complicate backtracking?
- How to prove optimality of the search depth?

## Why This Is Asked
This tests practical structuring of 3-valued reasoning via propagation on a single formula.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene 3-valued semantics: T>U>F; ¬ swaps T/F, U→U; ∨/∧ use max/min.
- Expression-level propagation and branch pruning.
- Backtracking search with partial assignments.

## Code Example
```javascript
function eval3(a,b,c){
  const not=(v)=> v==='T'? 'F' : v==='F'? 'T' : 'U';
  const or=(x,y)=> {
    const rank={'F':0,'U':1,'T':2};
    return rank[x] >= rank[y] ? x : y;
  };
  const and=(x,y)=> {
    const rank={'F':0,'U':1,'T':2};
    return rank[x] <= rank[y] ? x : y;
  };
  return and(or(a,b), or(not(c), a));
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- Give another satisfying assignment with all literals evaluable.
- How would you scale this to n variables and multiple formulas?

## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates your ability to design propagation strategies for tri-valued logic systems, specifically handling XOR operations in constraint networks with unknown values.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene three-valued logic with truth ordering T > U > F
- Three-valued XOR extension with unknown propagation
- Implication implemented as NOT A OR B with max semantics
- Local propagation ensuring no false constraint evaluations

## Code Example
```javascript
function not(a) { if(a === 'T') return 'F'; if(a === 'F') return 'T'; return 'U'; }
function xor(a, b) { if(a === 'U' || b === 'U') return 'U'; return a !== b ? 'T' : 'F'; }
function implies(a, b) { return not(a) === 'T' || b === 'T' ? 'T' : not(a) === 'U' || b === 'U' ? 'U' : 'F'; }
function propagate(variables) {
  // Iterative application of constraints until fixed point
  let changed;
  do {
    changed = false;
    // Apply each constraint using the three-valued operators
    const newV3 = xor(variables.V1, variables.V2);
    if(newV3 !== variables.V3) { variables.V3 = newV3; changed = true; }
    const newV5 = implies(not(variables.V2), variables.V4);
    if(newV5 !== variables.V5) { variables.V5 = newV5; changed = true; }
    // Continue with remaining constraints...
  } while(changed);
  return variables;
}
```

## How It Works
The propagation strategy iteratively applies constraints using Kleene semantics, ensuring that unknown values propagate appropriately while maintaining consistency. When a constraint involves an unknown variable, the result inherits the unknown state, preventing false evaluations while allowing partial information to flow through the network.

## Why This Is Asked
This tests three-valued reasoning under uncertainty, constraint propagation techniques, and handling rule priorities in practical policy evaluation systems.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene three-valued logic for handling unknown information
- Rule prioritization and conflict resolution
- Backtracking search with constraint propagation
- Truth functions: ¬U = U; ∧/∨ as min/max; A → B = ¬A ∨ B

## Code Example

```javascript
// Kleene three-valued logic operations
function kleeneNot(x) { 
  return x === 'T' ? 'F' : x === 'F' ? 'T' : 'U'; 
}

function kleeneAnd(a, b) { 
  return (a === 'F' || b === 'F') ? 'F' : 
         (a === 'T' && b === 'T') ? 'T' : 'U'; 
}

function kleeneOr(a, b) { 
  return (a === 'T' || b === 'T') ? 'T' : 
         (a === 'F' && b === 'F') ? 'F' : 'U'; 
}

function kleeneImplies(a, b) { 
  return kleeneOr(kleeneNot(a), b); 
}

// Rule evaluation with priority handling
function evaluateRule(rule, assignment) {
  const { antecedent, consequent } = rule;
  const antecedentValue = evaluateExpression(antecedent, assignment);
  const consequentValue = evaluateExpression(consequent, assignment);
  return kleeneImplies(antecedentValue, consequentValue);
}
```

## Solution Strategy
The backtracking algorithm systematically explores assignments while respecting Kleene semantics and rule priorities. At each step, it propagates constraints and prunes branches where higher-priority rules would evaluate to false. The search terminates when a satisfying assignment is found or all possibilities are exhausted.

## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses the ability to translate graph-based access policy constraints into a three-valued logical solver while managing constraint satisfaction risks. The directed graph structure introduces transitive reasoning requirements, making the problem more realistic than handling independent logical clauses.

## Key Concepts
- Three-valued logic propagation using Kleene semantics (T > U > F)
- Arc-consistency enforcement on directed constraint graphs
- Not-both-true constraint handling and conflict detection
- Backtracking strategies for partial truth assignments

## Code Example
```javascript
function propagate(vals, edges) {
  // vals: {N1:'T'|'F'|'U',...}
  // edges: [[from, to], ...]
  let changed = true;
  while (changed) {
    changed = false;
    for (const [from, to] of edges) {
      if (vals[from] === 'T' && vals[to] === 'F') {
        return false; // Constraint violated
      }
      if (vals[from] === 'T' && vals[to] === 'U') {
        vals[to] = 'T';
        changed = true;
      }
    }
  }
  return true;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to reason about tri-state logic in practical hardware-like constraints and to design propagation mechanisms that preserve unknowns.

## Key Concepts

- Kleene three-valued semantics for ¬, ∧, ∨, and → as ¬A ∨ B
- Fixed-point propagation and backtracking in CSP-like constraint sets
- Detecting unsatisfiable partial interpretations while maintaining at least one U

## Code Example

```javascript
function not(x){ if(x==='T') return 'F'; if(x==='F') return 'T'; return 'U'; }
function or(x,y){ if(x==='T' || y==='T') return 'T'; if(x==='U' || y==='U') return 'U'; return 'F'; }
function and(x,y){ if(x==='F' || y==='F') return 'F'; if(x==='U' || y==='U') return 'U'; return 'T'; }
function implies(a,b){ return or(not(a), b); }

// Example evaluation
let A='T', B='U', C='T', D='F';
let c1 = implies(A,B);
let c2 = implies(not(B), C);
let c3 = implies(or(C,D), B);
let c4 = implies(and(A,D), not(C));
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you scale the propagation to hundreds of variables and arbitrary Horn-like constraints?
- How does the approach change if you require at least two U values in every satisfying assignment?

## Why This Is Asked
This tests reasoning with three-valued logic in policy-like constraints, ensuring candidates can propagate values and avoid false evaluations when handling uncertainty.

## Key Concepts
- Three-valued logic with T/F/U truth values
- Implication defined as ¬X ∨ Y
- Constraint propagation and backtracking in constraint satisfaction problems
- Handling unknown values without forcing false evaluations

## Code Example
```javascript
function implies(X,Y){
  const not = {T:'F',F:'T',U:'U'};
  const max = (a,b)=> (a==='T'||b==='T')?'T':(a==='U'||b==='U')?'U':'F';
  return max(not[X], Y);
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

This question tests the ability to design and analyze non-classical logics using Kleene's 3-valued semantics with a novel XOR operator within a constraint network. It requires demonstrating systematic backtracking with unit propagation while handling partial information, and verifying consistency with unknown values in logical implications.

## Key Concepts

- Kleene 3-valued logic semantics
- XOR operator extension in paraconsistent settings
- Backtracking with unit propagation techniques
- Consistency maintenance with unknown values

## Code Example

```javascript
// Kleene 3-valued logic implementation
class KleeneLogic {
  static VALUES = { T: true, F: false, U: 'unknown' };

  static NOT(x) {
    return x === 'U' ? 'U' : !x;
  }

  static AND(x, y) {
    if (x === 'F' || y === 'F') return 'F';
    if (x === 'U' || y === 'U') return 'U';
    return 'T';
  }

  static OR(x, y) {
    if (x === 'T' || y === 'T') return 'T';
    if (x === 'U' || y === 'U') return 'U';
    return 'F';
  }

  static XOR(x, y) {
    return this.OR(this.AND(x, this.NOT(y)), this.AND(this.NOT(x), y));
  }

  static IMPLIES(x, y) {
    if (x === 'F') return 'T';
    if (x === 'U' || y === 'U') return 'U';
    return y;
  }
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests reasoning about three-valued logical systems in constraint satisfaction problems, particularly handling partial truth values and implementing efficient propagation mechanisms.

## Key Concepts
- Łukasiewicz three-valued logic: domain {0, 0.5, 1} with specific semantic definitions for implication, negation, disjunction, and conjunction
- Forward-chaining propagation in multi-valued constraint systems
- Bound propagation and domain pruning for partial assignments
- Constraint satisfaction with unknown/indeterminate values

## Code Example
```javascript
function lukasiewiczImplication(a, b) {
    return Math.min(1, 1 - a + b);
}

function lukasiewiczNegation(x) {
    return 1 - x;
}

function lukasiewiczDisjunction(x, y) {
    return Math.min(1, x + y);
}

function lukasiewiczConjunction(x, y) {
    return Math.max(0, x + y - 1);
}

function forwardChainPropagation(variables, constraints) {
    let changed = true;
    while (changed) {
        changed = false;
        for (const constraint of constraints) {
            const result = evaluateConstraint(constraint, variables);
            if (result === 0) {
                return false; // Contradiction found
            }
        }
        // Apply domain pruning based on constraint satisfaction
        changed = pruneDomains(variables, constraints);
    }
    return true;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests 3-valued propagation in a practical policy setting, ensuring candidates handle unknowns in real constraint systems.

## Key Concepts

- Kleene logic: T>U>F; ¬ maps T↔F, ¬U=U; ∨/∧ use max/min semantics.
- Constraint propagation with backtracking to avoid F conclusions.

## Code Example

```javascript
// Minimal Kleene implication sketch (for illustration)
function kleeneImp(A,B){
  const not = v => (v==='T'?'F': v==='F'?'T':'U');
  // simplistic placeholder: avoid F when A is not definitively true
  return (A==='T' && B==='F') ? 'F' : 'U';
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How to detect unsatisfiability with remaining U values?
- How does variable ordering affect worst-case exploration?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to apply paraconsistent LP semantics to CSP-style constraint solving, including constructing a concrete model and a propagation strategy.

## Key Concepts

- Priest's Logic of Paradox (LP)
- Paraconsistent 3-valued truth tables for ∨, ∧, ¬, →
- CSP backtracking with forward checking under LP
- Concrete satisfying assignment with at least one B

## Code Example

```javascript
// LP semantics for 3-valued logic (T > F, B = both)
function lpNot(v){ return v=== 'T' ? 'F' : v==='F' ? 'T' : 'B';}
function lpOr(a,b){ if(a==='T' || b==='T') return 'T'; if(a==='B' || b==='B') return 'B'; return 'F';}
function lpAnd(a,b){ if(a==='F' || b==='F') return 'F'; if(a==='T' && b==='T') return 'T'; return 'B';}
function lpImp(a,b){ // a -> b = (¬a) ∨ b
  return lpOr(lpNot(a), b);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How to detect unsatisfiable constraint sets efficiently in LP?
- How would you scale this to hundreds of variables with incremental propagation?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests design of tri-valued constraint systems with a custom operator and backtracking propagation, ensuring candidates reason about Kleene semantics and propagation rules.

## Key Concepts
- Kleene three-valued logic with T > U > F; ∧/∨ act as min/max.
- Custom operator Nand defined as not(and(x,y)).
- Backtracking propagation to prune domains and find a satisfying assignment.

## Code Example
```javascript
// Basic tri-valued lattice: T > U > F
const rank = { 'F':0, 'U':1, 'T':2 };
function not(x){ return x==='T'?'F': x==='F'?'T':'U'; }
function and(a,b){ return rank[a] <= rank[b] ? a : b; }
function or(a,b){ return rank[a] >= rank[b] ? a : b; }
function nand(a,b){ return not(and(a,b)); }
function implies(p,q){ return or(not(p), q); }

// sample assignment
let F1='T', F2='F', F3='U', F4='F';
console.log(implies(or(F1,F2), F3)); // U
console.log(and(F2,F4)); // F
console.log(nand(F3,F4)); // T
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you generalize to N flags and arbitrary constraint sets?
- What changes when moving to a 4-valued logic or alternative lattices?

## Why This Is Asked

Assesses ability to design a small 3-valued constraint solver and to enforce an exact-one-U constraint, a common pattern in policy engines and static analyzers.

## Key Concepts

- Kleene three-valued logic
- Constraint propagation
- Backtracking with pruning
- Exact-one constraint

## Code Example

```javascript
function satisfies(A,B,C){
  // A,B,C in {T,F,U}; returns true if all constraints not-F
  const not = v => v=== 'T' ? 'F' : v==='F' ? 'T' : 'U';
  const and = (x,y) => (x==='F'||y==='F')?'F':(x==='T'&&y==='T')?'T':'U';
  const or = (x,y) => (x==='T'||y==='T')?'T':(x==='F'&&y==='F')?'F':'U';
  const imp = (x,y) => not(x) || y;
  const c1 = imp(and(A,B), C);
  const c2 = imp(not(B), or(A,C));
  const c3 = imp(or(C, not(A)), B);
  return c1!=='F' && c2!=='F' && c3!=='F';
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you scale to N variables with the exact-one-U constraint?
- What pruning strategies speed up the search in larger rule sets?

